Because `Logger` is declared by a single tag, re-defining it with `Layer.succeed` in the test bundle swaps the implementation without touching the program.

```ts
import { Effect, Context, Layer } from "effect";

interface Clock { readonly now: () => number }
const Clock = Context.GenericTag<Clock>("app/Clock");

interface Counter { readonly tick: () => Effect.Effect<number> }
const Counter = Context.GenericTag<Counter>("app/Counter");

// Pure value — Layer.succeed.
const ClockLive = Layer.succeed(Clock, { now: () => Date.now() });

// Effectful construction (allocate a closure over a mutable ref) — Layer.effect.
const CounterLive = Layer.effect(
  Counter,
  Effect.sync(() => {
    let n = 0;
    return { tick: () => Effect.sync(() => ++n) };
  })
);

export const BaseLayer = Layer.merge(ClockLive, CounterLive);
```

`Layer.succeed` takes a ready value; `Layer.effect` takes an `Effect` that produces the service — use it when construction needs I/O, allocation, or other effects.

```ts
import { Effect, Context, Layer } from "effect";

interface Config { readonly host: string }
interface Logger { readonly info: (msg: string) => Effect.Effect<void> }
interface Main { readonly run: () => Effect.Effect<void> }

const Config = Context.GenericTag<Config>("app/Config");
const Logger = Context.GenericTag<Logger>("app/Logger");
const Main = Context.GenericTag<Main>("app/Main");

const ConfigLive = Layer.succeed(Config, { host: "localhost" });
const LoggerLive = Layer.effect(
  Logger,
  Effect.succeed({ info: (m: string) => Effect.sync(() => console.log(m)) })
);
const MainLive = Layer.effect(
  Main,
  Effect.gen(function* () {
    const cfg = yield* Config;
    const log = yield* Logger;
    return { run: () => log.info(`main on ${cfg.host}`) };
  })
);

// v3 positional form; inner deps go in the second argument.
export const AppLayer = Layer.provide(MainLive, Layer.merge(ConfigLive, LoggerLive));
```

Instead of chaining `Layer.provide` once per dep, merge the dependencies into one layer and provide it in a single call — positional arguments in v3.

```ts
import { Effect, Context, Layer } from "effect";

interface A { readonly tag: "A" }
interface B { readonly tag: "B" }
interface C { readonly tag: "C" }
interface D { readonly tag: "D" }

const A = Context.GenericTag<A>("app/A");
const B = Context.GenericTag<B>("app/B");
const C = Context.GenericTag<C>("app/C");
const D = Context.GenericTag<D>("app/D");

const ALive = Layer.succeed(A, { tag: "A" });
const BLive = Layer.succeed(B, { tag: "B" });
const CLive = Layer.effect(C, Effect.succeed({ tag: "C" as const }));
const DLive = Layer.effect(D, Effect.succeed({ tag: "D" as const }));

// Flat variadic form.
export const AppLayer = Layer.mergeAll(ALive, BLive, CLive, DLive);
```

`Layer.mergeAll(...layers)` avoids the nested `merge(merge(...))` tree — easier to read and still type-checks the union of outputs.

`Layer.effect(Tag, builderEffect)` produces a service by running `builderEffect` once when the layer is provided. The builder is an `Effect<Service, E, R>` — its `R` channel names which upstream services it needs. Yield those services inside `Effect.gen`, close over them in the service's method closures, and return the final `Service` record. The builder runs lazily on first use and is memoised per layer.

